## 🧭 Why IP Addresses Exist

IP = the addressing scheme that lets devices find each other across networks. Without it, packets have no destination — like mail with no envelope.

---

## 🔢 IPv4 — The Legacy System

- **32-bit address**, written in **dotted-decimal notation**: 4 octets (8 bits each), 0–255, separated by dots
- Example: `192.168.1.1` → binary `11000000.10101000.00000001.00000001`

### The Exhaustion Problem
- Only **2³² ≈ 4.3 billion** possible addresses
- Explosive growth (PCs, phones, servers, IoT) burned through this space → **IPv4 exhaustion**

### Classful Addressing (historical)

| Class | First Octet Range | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| A | 1–126 | Very large networks |
| B | 128–191 | Medium/large networks |
| C | 192–223 | Small networks |
| D | 224–239 | Multicast (reserved) |
| E | 240–255 | Experimental (reserved) |

Inefficient — e.g. a Class C net gives 254 hosts even if you only need a handful.

### Subnetting (temporary fix)
Borrow bits from the **host** portion to create a **subnet** portion.

- **Network ID** — identifies the network
- **Host ID** — identifies a device within it
- **Subnet Mask** — 32-bit number; `1`s = network/subnet portion, `0`s = host portion

**Example:** `192.168.1.0/24` (mask `255.255.255.0`) → borrow 1 bit → `/25` (mask `255.255.255.128`)

| Subnet | Network ID | Usable Hosts | Broadcast |
|---|---|---|---|
| Subnet 1 | 192.168.1.0 | .1 – .126 | 192.168.1.127 |
| Subnet 2 | 192.168.1.128 | .129 – .254 | 192.168.1.255 |

### Private vs Public IPv4

| Class | Private Range | CIDR |
|---|---|---|
| A | 10.0.0.0 – 10.255.255.255 | /8 |
| B | 172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255 | /12 |
| C | 192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255 | /16 |

- Private addresses aren't routable on the public internet
- **NAT (Network Address Translation)** lets many private-IP devices share one public IP (done by your router)

